S1.T1.caption: TABLE I:  Communication and computation loads of secure aggregation frameworks in federated learning. Here N𝑁N is the total number of the users, L𝐿L is the model size, T𝑇T is the number of semi-honest users, D𝐷D is the number of dropouts, s𝑠s is the length of seeds for pseudo random generator.In this table, the last column indicates the maximum number of semi-honest users and dropouts that the scheme can tolerate.
S1.T1.footnotes: In this table, in order to have a fair comparison in terms of communication load, the design parameter in LightSecAgg is chosen such that it minimizes the communication loads.
references:
As an earlier and conference version of this manuscript, in [14]
, we propose SwiftAgg which reduces the server communication load via partitioning users into several groups and using Shamir’s secret sharing [15] to keep the local models private. SwiftAgg is able to achieve correct aggregation in presence of up to D𝐷D dropout users, with formally-proven the worst-case security guarantee against up to T𝑇T semi-honest users. Independently, similar ideas have been used in CodedSecAgg [16], but dropout users in groups have not been addressed and there is no formal definition and proof of privacy. The communication loads and the computation loads of the existing approaches are compared in Table I.

Table I compares different schemes for secure aggregation problem in terms of the communication and computation loads. For a fair comparison, we consider two metrics: the server communication load and the per-user communication load. Server communication load indicates the aggregated size of all messages which are sent or received by the server, and per-user communication load denotes the aggregated size of all messages which are sent by each user. Furthermore, server and per-user computations indicate the computation loads of the server and each user respectively. In this table, the computational complexity of the schemes in [12, 7, 14], and SwiftAgg+, is calculated based on Reed-Solomon decoding complexity [18]. Any improvements in this complexity can be applied to those schemes.

Compared with existing schemes, as shown in Table I, SwiftAgg+ significantly reduces the server communication load and per-user communication load, and for T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and N−D=𝒪​(N)𝑁𝐷𝒪𝑁N-D=\mathcal{O}(N),
it requires L​(1+𝒪​(1N))𝐿1𝒪1𝑁L(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N})) symbols for the server communication load and for T=o​(N)𝑇𝑜𝑁T=o(N) and D=o​(N)𝐷𝑜𝑁D=o(N), it requires L​(1+𝒪​(1N))𝐿1𝒪1𝑁L(1+\mathcal{O}(\frac{1}{N})) symbols for the per-user communication load.
Meanwhile, similar as LightSecAgg, the proposed SwiftAgg+ also enjoys small server computation complexity with worst-cast security guarantees.
